===Marriage=== On December 1, 1670,{{efn|The 21st day of the 11th month of [[:en:Kanbun (era)|Kanbun]] 9.}} Fusako entered the court of Emperor Reigen, one year her junior, as a court lady. On June 23, 1673,{{efn|The 9th day of the 5th month of Kanbun 13.}} the palace went up in flames, and the estate of ''[[udaijin]]'' [[:en:Konoe Motohiro|Konoe Motohiro]] was used as a temporary palace. This was not a new occurrence: in 1661,{{efn|The 1st month of [[Manji (era)|Manji]] 4.}} during the reign of the previous emperor [[:en:Emperor Go-Sai|Emperor Go-Sai]], another conflagration had led to the use of Motohiro's estate. On October 3, 1673,{{efn|The 23rd day of the 8th month of Kanbun 13.}} Fusako gave birth to her daughter {{Nihongo|Princess Masako|栄子内親王}}. In light of the great fire in [[Kyoto]] that had destroyed the palace, the [[:en:Japanese era name|era name]] was changed to [[:en:Enpō|Enpō]]. But on January 10, 1676,{{efn|The 25th day of the 11th month of Enpō 3.}} immediately after a new palace had been completed, the temporary one at Motohiro's estate caught flame in turn. Fusako and the emperor found refuge at the home of {{Nihongo|Yoshida Kaneyuki|吉田兼敬}} before entering the new palace two days later.
===Empress=== On January 1, 1683,{{efn|The 7th day of the 12th month of [[Tenna]] 2.}} Fusako was proclaimed {{Nihongo||准三后|jusangō}}, and on December 3{{efn|The 14th day of the 2nd month of Tenna 3.}} she was invested as ''[[:en:Chūgū|Chūgū]]''. She thereby became the emperor's legitimate wife—during the entire [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], this only happened four times. Reigen abdicated the throne on May 2, 1687,{{efn|The 21st day of the 3rd month of [[:en:Jōkyō|Jōkyō]] 4.}} in favor of Crown Prince Asahito, who then became [[:en:Emperor Higashiyama|Emperor Higashiyama]]. Accompanying this, Fusako was bestowed the honorary name Shinjōsaimon-in. In early 1695,{{efn|The 7th month of [[:en:Genroku|Genroku]] 8.}} the [[Tokugawa shogunate|shogunate]] presented her with 1,000 ''koku'' of land.
Takatsukasa Fusako died on May 19, 1712.{{efn|The 14th day of the 4th month of [[Shōtoku (era)|Shōtoku]] 4.}} Her grave is located at [[Tsuki no wa no misasagi]] in [[:en:Higashiyama-ku, Kyoto|Higashiyama-ku]], [[Kyoto]].
